Orchestrates a two-stage brief pipeline: resolve a backlog item via `status_item`, gather a grounded dossier through a read-only `claude -p` pass, then produce the brief either interactively (human interview writes it) or headlessly (runner captures stdout and writes it). This is the top-level flow tying together `Fs`, `Claude`, `status_item`, and prompt files on disk.

`run<F: Fs, C: Claude>(fs: &F, claude: &C, cfg: &Config, target: &Path) -> Result<String, BriefError>` is the entry point: reads `docs/STATUS.md` (missing file tolerated, falls back to empty string + free-text treatment), resolves the item via `status_item::resolve`, logs to stderr whether the request matched a backlog row or fell back to custom text, runs `gather`, then dispatches to `headless_plan` or `interactive_plan` based on `cfg.headless`. Returns the cwd-relative output path on success.

Both gather and plan stages set their working directory to `target` (the target repo, not this crate) so the target's own context hooks (including its `ctx-context` binary, allowlisted in `GATHER_TOOLS` as `Bash(target/debug/ctx-context *)`) ground the read. Gather is restricted to `Read`/`Grep`/`Glob`/that one `Bash` pattern — no edit/write tools, enforced by `GATHER_TOOLS`.

`headless_plan` writes the brief itself via `fs.write` after capturing Claude's stdout. `interactive_plan` does not write anything — the interactive Claude session writes the file directly to `cfg.out_rel` (repo-relative), and this function only verifies `fs.exists(&cfg.out_fs)` afterward, returning `BriefError::BriefNotWritten` if the session didn't produce it. `plan_user` builds the shared user message and appends output instructions only for the interactive path (`out_rel: Some`), since headless mode's brief comes back on stdout instead.

Prompt files are loaded from `cfg.prompts_dir` by fixed name (`briefer-gather.md`, `briefer-plan-headless.md`, `briefer-plan.md`); a missing file maps to `BriefError::PromptMissing`. `stage_start`/`stage_done` write timing progress lines to stderr unconditionally and swallow write errors — not seamed through `Fs`, deliberately untested via fakes. `Config` carries two variants of the output path (`out_rel` for the target repo's cwd, `out_fs` for this process's cwd) — conflating them will break either the interactive session's write target or this file's own existence check/write.